deck: Founder and leader of the Y-Men.
description:
Origin

Professor Yavio was once a brilliant young geneticist. He believed that hidden within certain individuals' DNA were genes for superpowers and that they could be used to benefit mankind. His collegues believed him to be a nutcase. As a result, his funding stopped. Yavio sold some of his inventions to gather money to further study this 'alternate genes'. He discovered the genes could be brought out with vitamorph radiation. Despite the risk, he used himself as his first test subject. His dormant powers, telekinesis, came out. He then adopted a group of children with the most potential he could find and exposed them to the vitamorph rays to bring out their various abilities. The group was called the Y-Men. He trained them at the Yavio School For Freakishly Gifted But Otherwise Completely Normal Students.

deck: A butterfly enthusiast who was accidentally irradiated by a chunk of the moon
description:
Origin

Travelling in Central America while hunting butterflies, Martin Kell was irradiated by a chunk of the Moon that fell to Earth.

Creation

Martin Kell was created byBernard Baily and an unknown writer. He made his first appearance in House of Mystery #97.

Major Story Arcs

The Moon Monster

Mutated into a strange creature by the radiation, the injured and disoriented Kell wanders into a nearby village. The villagers flee in horror from his appearance, while Kell's new powers accidentally affect the ocean, causing a massive tidal wave. Kell flees into the woods, where he encounters a tribe of natives, who mistake him for their moon god. Dying and delirious, he stumbles out of their encampment to chase after a butterfly, and is struck by lightning. Coincidentally, the lightning splits a nearby mountain, fulfilling the natives' prophecy. Kell is returned to normal by the lightning strike.

Powers and Abilities

Due to the radiation, Kell briefly acquired a massive, Moon-like head and disfigured skin. Like the Moon, he has a gravitational effect on the tide, and his nearness to large bodies of water will draw the water towards him.
name: The Moon Monster

deck: In the traditions of pre-cataclysmic Atlantis, Suula was the goddess of the sky.
description: Shalako, brother of King Orin the First of Poseidonis was one of her priests. Orin incurred Suula's wrath when he insulted her by building a protective dome around Poseidonis, cutting the city off from the heavens, and by extension, from Suula herself. It is believed that Suula was responsible for bringing the meteor to Earth that caused the Great Deluge that ultimately sank Atlantis.
name: Suula

deck: Loma was one of the 11 wives of Shalako and mother of Dardanus.
description:
After the Great Deluge, Shalako announces that his followers and he will be leaving Poseidonis using a series of underground tunnels that connect all of the great cities. He intends on leading an exodus from Poseidonis to settle in the ruins of what was once the sister-city of Tritonis.

Shalako has forsaken the grace of the sky goddess Suula in favor of the dark gods. He uses his magic to create a pocket of hard water that protects his wife Loma and he. He uses this same magic to create a giant hard-water dome that shields Tritonis from the crushing ocean water, but the dark gods demand a sacrifice. Shalako murders his wife and offers up her blood as a gift to the gods. His son, Dardanus, witnesses the murder of his mother
name: Loma

deck: An immortal madman who sought to destroy the world in order to end his own life. An enemy of Airboy. He made his first appearance in Airboy comics #71 (January 1950).
description:
Born in prehistoric times during a cosmic event when all the planets in the universe came into alignment, Zzed was cursed with immortality. Over the centuries, he grew weary of his existence and eventually decided to destroy all life in order to end his own. His schemes were repeatedly thwarted by the original Airboy, but Zzed escaped to try again.

Many years later, Zzed (under the telepathic influence of Nine-Crocodile) devised his most elaborate plan to end the universe when the "total eclipse" once again came into alignment. Heroes from multiple realities joined together to prevent the disaster. Due to the interference of Tachyon, the unleashed cosmic power did not kill Zzed, but instead brought him great enlightenment. Altered both physically and spiritually, Zzed joined forces with the other heroes in order to stop Nine-Crocodile, the true mastermind behind Zzed's scheme. The reformed Zzed rechristened himself "Doctor Eclipse."
name: Zzed

The prince made his first Bd appearance in les chevaliers d'Émeraude, tome 1- Les enfants magiques (August 2011) and his first novel appearance was in Les chevaliers d'Émeraude, tome 1-Le feu dans le ciel (2003).

deck: Britton, son of Cole, was the second official chronist of Atlantis.
description:
He inherited this work from his deceased uncle Albart, but never agreed the way Albart idealized Shalako and underestimated King Orin. Britton's style of writing was rather poetic, even during the civil war between Shalakites and Orin's followers.

Subsequently, he wrote about the self-exile of Shalako and the shalakites from Poseidonis to refound the abandoned city of Tritonis and referred to Shalako as "insane". Britton became a close follower of Orin and always supported him. He recorded in his chronicles all the scientific advances, including the serum that allowed people to breathe underwater.

One of his last writings by Britton was Shalako's death, caused by angry shalakities whose human legs transformed into amphibian/monster legs due to a curse against them casted by Shalako himself.

Britton died of black flu (he was one the first victims). He had no children, so the legacy of the Atlantis Chronicles continues through his younger sister, Illya.
name: Britton

deck: Thorne was an Atlantean scientist who invented a serum that altered an Atlantean's physiology, enabling them to survive underwater.
description: King Orin did not wish to spread false hope to the people of Poseidonis, so he made sure to keep Thorne's work a secret. Orin volunteered to test the serum on himself first. The serum worked, and Orin was able to leave the domed city and survive beneath the ocean. The experiment was a miraculous success and Orin quickly dispensed the serum to everyone in Poseidonis, transforming them into an amphibious species.
name: Thorne

Illya witnessed princess Cora's 14th birthday, when Dardanus (Shalako's son, supposed to be dead) reappeared alive and stabbed Bazil. She even had the chance to punch Dardanus after that episode.[1]

Most of her writings were told by his friend Bazil. However, she always wanted to be in the first line, specially during the battle between tritonians and people from Poseidonis. During that battle, she was found dead. Someone attacked her from behind.

The next official chronist of Atlantis would be her son Regin.

deck: Regin was the fourth Atlantis chronicler after his mother Illya's death.
description:
He was Fiona's lover and later her husband. He wrote almost everything about the war between Poseidonians, led by Orin and Bazil, and Tritonians, led by Dardanus and Kordax.

During the battle for Atlantis, Kordax attacked Regin and was about to kill him, but Fiona appeared and defeated his older half-brother. He also witnessed the fight of Orin against Dardanus and the spirit of Shalako. His interpretation about that fight was always doubted by his wife, Queen Fiona, who tried to find a logical explanation, ruling out the presence of spirits.

The last mayor episode he wrote was Kordax's punishment (the loss of his left arm and banishment), under the orders of Queen Cora.
name: Regin

deck: Haumond was the third and last son of King Honsu and Queen Lorelei.
description:
He was born in Atlantis several years after his brothers Kraken and Atlan. King Honsu and Kraken were great warriors, while Haumond was more peaceful. However, Haumond accompanied their father on Atlantis' conquest of surface world.

When atlantean warriors failed to conquer Egypt, Haumond was left behind and thought dead. Haumond was brought before Ramses, who revealed that he was actually a descendant of the original atlantean explorers sent out by Orin I.

In Athens, Honsu challenged the Greeks to send their greatest warrior against his son Kraken. Kraken was killed by the Athenian champion—who turned out to be...Haumond. As Atlan's sorcerous powers grew, he gave Haumond a potion which allowed him to live on land longer than other Atlanteans and extended his life span. However, after centuries, he ceased taking the potions. In Egypt, Haumond became a priest and told Solon (athenian stateman) the ancient story of of Atlantis. After his death, Atlan released Haumond's body back to the ocean, where he belonged.
name: Haumond

deck: Yekop is one of the six new guardians of the Green Lantern universe.
description:
Yekop is one of the six new guardians that have taken the mantle of Guardians of the Universe, after Sinestro and Atrocitus killed the previous guardians.

Rise of the Third Army

For eons, Yekop and the other guardians were hidden and sealed as wardens in the Chamber of Shadows, along with Volthoom, the First Lantern, who they were assigned to oversee. When Yekop and the other guardians finally come face-to-face with their estranged siblings, they are shocked to see how emotionless the latter have become and briefly provide resistance, which results in one of Yekop's brothers being killed. They are again locked into the Chamber of Shadows until finally Simon Baz releases them.

Later, after Volthoom and the Guardians (save for Ganthet and Sayd) are killed, Yekop and the other guardians step into the role of Guardians of the Universe, though they relinquish their responsibility to Hal Jordan in order to experience the universe they had been earlier denied.

Light's Out

Yekop and the others begin playing a larger role at the end of Light's Out. After their voyage across the universe, they seem to have been caught up to speed on the comings-and-goings and are able to aid Kyle Rayner as both a white lantern and the host of the emotional spectrum's entities. With the end of Light's Out, they are seen surveying the wall that protects whatever is beyond the edge of the universe and become the only beings that know of Kyle Rayner's survival.

description:
Origin

The child of two performance artists, Crystal almost dies during one of her mother's performances, but is rescued by Charles Rowland. After she recovers at the hospital, she decides to travel to St. Hilarions to find her rescuer.

Creation

Crystal was created by Toby Litt and Mark Buckingham for their series Dead Boy Detectives.

description:
Douwe Dabbert is a small gnome- like old man. He has a magic knapsack that always gives him what he needs. He inherited the knapsack from his grandfather who, as Dabbert usually says 'Could do a bit of magic'.

His magic knapsack only answers to Dabbert, when someone else looks trough it they usually find it empty or full of sand or mud.

Dabbert travels the world with his knapsack and always finds himself getting into adventures often fighting other magical beings, in a nice and orderly fashion.

The series started in 1975 and was created by Thom Roep and Piet Wijn.
